  <chapter>
    <title>Presentation of VISHNU</title>
    <section>
      <title>What is VISHNU ?</title>
      <para>VISHNU offers to end-users the capability of running computation tasks (jobs) on remote servers through a simple
        interface that offers performance and interoperability with different kind of batch scheduler softwares running locally
        on the servers. VISHNU also offers files management services to create, modify and transfer files on remote hosts using
        secure transfer protocols. The VISHNU system is also capable of monitoring the performance of the servers and to recover
        automatically from server failures.
      </para>
      <para>The VISHNU software consists of a client part that provides both command-line executables and C++ shared libraries for
        integration into an application, and a server part that is based on the <ulink url="http://graal.ens-lyon.fr/DIET">DIET</ulink>
        middleware for remote invokation of distributed services. Other user interfaces are provided on top of the C++ API using SWIG
        wrappers: currently it is available as Python module and Web services server.
      </para>
      <para>VISHNU is a modular system where each module can be deployed individually on a server to provide a subset of all VISHNU
        services. For example the TMS module can be deployed on one server for providing jobs handling services, while other
        VISHNU services (user mgmt, files mgmt, etc.) are served from another host. This allows a better performance by reducing 
        the load on each server.
      </para>
    </section>
    
